The royal library of the Fatimites consisted of one hundred thousand manuscripts, elegantly transcribed and splendidly bound, which were lent, without jealousy or avarice, to the students of Cairo. Yet this collefiion must appear moderate, if we can believe that the Ommiades of Spain had formed a library of six hundred thousand volumes, forty-four of which were employed in the mere catalogue. Their capital, Cordo-va, with the adjacent towns of Malaga, Ameria, and Murcia, had given birth to more than three hundred writers, and above seventy public libraries were opened in the cities of the An- dalufian kingdom.
